1
00:00:00,340 --> 00:00:15,040
[Music] Before we begin, it seems appropriate to make a diversion.

2
00:00:15,040 --> 00:00:26,689
Today's discussion stemmed from an unmaterialized debate with many Russian philologists, translators, and literary critics, who are accustomed to placing Don Quixote and Odysseus on the same level, talking about them

3
00:00:26,689 --> 00:00:31,520
in the same breath, as cunning wanderers. It seems to me,

4
00:00:31,520 --> 00:00:44,929
that such a comparison is not only superficial, but it is also of the sort that can insult and outrage both participants, as if to say, how can I even be compared to that? It’s like comparing Brodsky with

5
00:00:44,929 --> 00:00:50,539
Yevtushenko or Nabokov with Dostoevsky. Of course,

6
00:00:50,539 --> 00:00:58,670
Odysseus and Quixote are destined to be seen together because they embody two major journeys of European literature.

7
00:00:58,670 --> 00:01:03,260
However, in their case, beneath the unity of form lies a contentual opposition.

8
00:01:03,260 --> 00:01:16,189
Don Quixote is not just not a successor or reincarnation of Odysseus; Don Quixote, in almost all respects, is the anti-Odysseus. This is precisely what we shall discuss today.

9
00:01:16,189 --> 00:01:21,439
My name is Armen Zakharian, and you're watching the literature-centric channel "Armen and Fyodor". Here

10
00:01:21,439 --> 00:01:27,500
in our close circle, we set Don Quixote and Odysseus against each other. Today we will encounter real magic.

11
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:36,399
We will attempt to transfer ourselves to the only place they could meet and imagine what that meeting might have been like.

12
00:01:36,399 --> 00:01:52,590
Previously, I have talked about each of them separately: there are episodes on the channel about what it means to be an Odysseus and what it means to be a Don Quixote. So if you want to get

13
00:01:52,590 --> 00:02:02,910
the maximal aesthetic pleasure from our conversation today, I recommend listening to those first.

14
00:02:02,910 --> 00:02:13,330
So, Don Quixote and Odysseus. It would be wrong to deny that there are a number of obvious features that unite them. They are both warriors: Odysseus — a king,

15
00:02:13,330 --> 00:02:24,460
leader of the army at Troy, Don Quixote — a knight. Both constantly find themselves in difficult situations and seek a way out. Both are heroes acting,

16
00:02:24,460 --> 00:02:30,550
they refuse to accept the status quo, they affect the world around them. Finally, both

17
00:02:30,550 --> 00:02:40,600
have been dubbed ingenious, but this coincidence is observed only in their Russian incarnations. In their original tongues

18
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:50,260
Don Quixote is "ingenioso", ingenious, whereas Odysseus — even in the text of Quixote itself — is "prudente", sensible. In a word, all these coincidences

19
00:02:50,260 --> 00:02:59,200
are no more than similarities of costume. The main thing that unites Odysseus and Don Quixote is the wandering, the constant movement.

20
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:04,480
But it is from this similarity that significant differences arise. Do you know why

21
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:16,780
famous hobbit Bilbo Baggins from Tolkien's tale cannot be placed in the same category with Odysseus and Quixote? Because his story is there and back again.

22
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:26,440
Don Quixote is only there, Odysseus — back. The whole meaning of Odysseus's journey is the return home, which is what the Greeks called "nostos". The essence

23
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:38,070
of Quixote's movement is quite the opposite — he seeks to break free from his home, to get out into the world, to go as far as possible. In this sense, Don Quixote chooses what

24
00:03:38,070 --> 00:03:47,310
the same Greeks called "kóleos" and opposed to "nostos", the return. So Odysseus and Quixote both are in motion,

25
00:03:47,310 --> 00:03:49,200
but in opposite directions. Thus,

26
00:03:49,200 --> 00:04:00,390
from the very beginning they find themselves facing each other with the same strength of movement but different application vectors. They converge, yet

27
00:04:00,390 --> 00:04:03,480
if Don Quixote is galloping from point A to point B,

28
00:04:03,480 --> 00:04:10,200
Odysseus at this time is sailing from point B to point A. What will happen? Something is certain — sooner

29
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:16,770
or later they will meet, and we even know where. But this will be later,

30
00:04:16,770 --> 00:04:24,500
while at the very start, at the maximum distance from each other, Quixote and Odysseus are most alike. They both sit

31
00:04:24,500 --> 00:04:33,990
in captivity: one on the island of the nymph Calypso, the other in his home behind the endless reading of knightly novels. However, even

32
00:04:33,990 --> 00:04:39,900
the nature of their captivity is already different: Odysseus is tormented physically, Don Quixote mentally. Thus,

33
00:04:39,900 --> 00:04:45,450
as opposites attract, they are propelled towards one another.

34
00:04:45,450 --> 00:04:51,660
The closer they come, the less they have in common. Don Quixote is extremely serious

35
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:55,440
in everything he does and therefore infinitely comical. In the end, where everyone

36
00:04:55,440 --> 00:05:07,860
makes fun of him, one of the characters will say: the benefit of Quixote and his reason cannot compare to the pleasure his folly brings.

37
00:05:07,860 --> 00:05:17,460
Odysseus often jokes at others' expense, but heaven forbid anyone else jokes about him. Don Quixote is constantly beaten,

38
00:05:17,460 --> 00:05:27,390
pelted with stones, caged, repeatedly thrashed, his face scratched, and in one episode, he is almost crucified.

39
00:05:27,390 --> 00:05:41,520
Odysseus, however, is invulnerable — he enters the Cyclops' cave, sails between Scylla and Charybdis, survives a shipwreck, losing companion after companion, but emerges from Poseidon's stirred waters relatively untouched. At decisive moments, no one can

40
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:47,910
even touch him, let alone beat him. Don

41
00:05:47,910 --> 00:05:58,169
Quixote is gullible, perpetually deceived, lied to, and endlessly manipulated for public amusement. Odysseus is cautious and calculating; he

42
00:05:58,169 --> 00:06:05,070
trusts no one; moreover, he deceives everyone, lies, feigns, twists the truth, and blends in.

43
00:06:05,070 --> 00:06:17,250
Naive Don Quixote once said: one cannot and should not call deception that which has a noble goal. For Odysseus, the end always justifies the means. Quixote

44
00:06:17,250 --> 00:06:21,000
is self-assured and arrogant to a certain point,

45
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:31,440
completely free of doubt. Odysseus might be arrogant, but generally, he evaluates himself and his capabilities more soberly, and has the tendency to doubt.

46
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:36,960
From this sobriety of Odysseus and the arrogance of Quixote comes another difference.

47
00:06:36,960 --> 00:06:42,830
Odysseus is extremely grounded, Quixote extremely lofty. He is, after all, a knight,

48
00:06:42,830 --> 00:06:47,490
speaks of honor, valor, and bravery. Of course, his courage is more often

49
00:06:47,490 --> 00:06:53,850
laughable, but he really does step into the cage with lions. Odysseus, however,

50
00:06:53,850 --> 00:07:03,440
talks far more often about the stomach: throughout all of the Iliad, all the heroes combined mention the stomach's power over man less frequently than Odysseus does in

51
00:07:03,440 --> 00:07:06,300
his personal epic.

52
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:20,000
Each tirade about the stomach begins with "that suffering is of course terrible," and ends with "there is nothing baser than our awful stomach" and "it would be nice to have a bite to eat."

53
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:29,470
The main irony of this comparison, of course, is that Odysseus here is not just the anti-Quixote, who fasts and feeds on wild acorns. Odysseus here is the spitting image of Sancho

54
00:07:29,470 --> 00:07:35,600
Panza. Don Quixote is a very poor strategist. As

55
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:49,100
a leader, he is a real catastrophe — under his command, Sancho, who dreamed of becoming a governor, becomes a laughingstock. Odysseus

56
00:07:49,100 --> 00:08:00,070
is a leader: charismatic, calculating, and ruthless. Under such command, even death is glorious. Odysseus is wise, Don Quixote is mad.

57
00:08:00,070 --> 00:08:12,290
Odyssey is a king, Don Quixote is a holy fool. Odysseus is an Old Testament God-punisher, Don Quixote is a New Testament Christ.

58
00:08:12,290 --> 00:08:23,839
[Music] And so, being complete opposites, they come to a single point. We were not

59
00:08:23,839 --> 00:08:32,779
warned about this in school textbooks, but the route from A to B and back passes through hell. Both Odysseus and Don Quixote

60
00:08:32,779 --> 00:08:38,479
descend into the underworld, and this, of course, is the only possible meeting point on their journey.

61
00:08:38,479 --> 00:08:48,079
For Odysseus, it's a descent into the realm of the dead, for Don Quixote it's a descent into the Cave of Montesinos. Yet, even in this, the heroes remain

62
00:08:48,079 --> 00:08:54,170
themselves. Odysseus goes there unwillingly because he is presented with no other means to reach his desired goal.

63
00:08:54,170 --> 00:09:09,470
When he learns of the need to visit the underworld, Homer describes his reaction as "rolling in bed and weeping," and his first question after his tears was: "And who will guide me there?" Don Quixote, however,

64
00:09:09,470 --> 00:09:20,319
descends into the Cave of Montesinos voluntarily, without escort or preliminaries, because Quixote considers himself a hero, and a hero must face trials.

65
00:09:20,319 --> 00:09:37,180
Just before the descent, he notices that he and Sancho forgot to bring a bell to signal above, an excellent reason to postpone the adventure.

66
00:09:37,180 --> 00:09:48,460
But knights do not retreat — the meeting must occur, and Quixote descends into the cave. And then the most frightening thing happens:

67
00:09:48,460 --> 00:09:58,270
Odysseus does not arrive. According to all calculations, by the logic of events, by the inheritance of heroic experience, he was supposed to be there. But Odysseus is practical, he

68
00:09:58,270 --> 00:10:06,720
goes to the realm of the dead for a prophecy from the old man Tiresias. The mad Quixote does not interest him.

69
00:10:06,720 --> 00:10:12,280
At the bottom of the damp cave, in the pitch darkness, the knight remains alone. It is then that he

70
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:19,260
first encounters his own disbelief, his own madness. Standing in

71
00:10:19,260 --> 00:10:33,820
total darkness, Quixote wonders: if Odysseus isn’t here, then perhaps none of the rest — the castles and giants, princesses and islands — existed either? In

72
00:10:33,820 --> 00:10:43,060
the afterlife checkpoint of their routes, Odysseus boldly turns his ship towards new trials, having left the worst behind.

73
00:10:43,060 --> 00:10:56,839
For him, nothing has changed — for Hades is tangible to Odysseus, and the most rational thing now is to simply keep following the plan, to avoid unpleasantly having to enter it again.

74
00:10:56,839 --> 00:10:59,810
But what is good for Odysseus spells death for Quixote. And

75
00:10:59,810 --> 00:11:11,690
after passing this point of non-meeting, he begins to doubt, and spots of common sense appear in the tapestry of his imagination, fatal for a madman.

76
00:11:11,690 --> 00:11:17,750
Quixote now begins to tread nervously in place, gazing inward with growing fear.

77
00:11:17,750 --> 00:11:24,950
His journey turns into a wandering of those corners of consciousness he should rather not explore at all.

78
00:11:24,950 --> 00:11:34,940
Now their paths will never cross again: each exits his underworld renewed and proceeds on his own way. Odysseus has new challenges ahead,

79
00:11:34,940 --> 00:11:45,100
but then — a triumphant return, a faithful wife, a loving son, and a reckoning with enemies. But as for

80
00:11:45,100 --> 00:12:06,380
Don Quixote, he will end his path as a knight, calling himself reckless and daring, having said of himself: "I stood up for the humiliated and rectified wrongs, punished insolence, convinced giants, and trod on monsters, and there’s no deed beyond human capabilities that I haven’t accomplished."

81
00:12:06,380 --> 00:12:20,620
This daring madman will end his path with perhaps the saddest assessment he could reach: "I don't know if I'm exactly good,

82
00:12:20,620 --> 00:12:27,140
but I can say I'm not bad." This is Armen Zakharian.

83
00:12:27,140 --> 00:12:36,799
Until next time. [Music].

